mt_raw:
The Chief Executive of the HKMA is appointed by the Financial Secretary, and thus the HKMA is accountable to the public through the Financial Secretary. As the HKMA’s powers are conferred by legislation enacted by the Legislative Council, the HKMA is also accountable to the public through the Legislative Council. In addition, the HKMA recognizes its broader responsibility to promote public understanding of its role and objectives, and to closely monitor issues of public concern. In carrying out its daily work and maintaining extensive engagement with the community, the HKMA steadfastly strives to enhance transparency and maintain an open policy. This policy has two main objectives:
- To ensure, subject to market sensitivity, commercial confidentiality, and statutory restrictions on disclosure of confidential information, that the financial sector and the public are as fully informed as possible about the HKMA’s work;
- To ensure that the HKMA keeps a finger on the pulse of society and responds appropriately to public opinion.

- The successful launch of the Faster Payment System (FPS), fully connecting different banks and stored value facilities (collectively known as "e-wallets");
- Issuance of the Open API Framework for the banking sector and promotion of industry-wide implementation of open APIs;
- Enhancement of fintech research and talent training;
- Strengthening cross-border fintech cooperation;
- Revision of the "Guideline on Authorization of Virtual Banks" and processing of virtual bank license applications;
- Smooth operation of the upgraded version of the "Fintech Supervisory Sandbox" (FSS 2.0); and
- Expansion of "Banking Made Easy" to promote the adoption of regtech by banks.

(a) Capital preservation;
(b) Ensuring that the entire monetary base is at all times fully backed by highly liquid US dollar assets;
(c) Ensuring sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) Subject to the above (a) to (c), seeking to maximize investment returns to preserve the long-term purchasing power of the Fund.

- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and financial liabilities, including relevant control measures;
- Evaluating and testing control measures, including relevant application controls of computer systems;
- Obtaining confirmations regarding the valuation, existence, rights and obligations, and completeness of financial assets and financial liabilities;
- For market-quoted prices, verifying prices against independent sources;
- For valuation techniques using inputs based on observable market data, evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the assumptions, and verifying the inputs against independent sources; and
- For valuation techniques using significant unobservable inputs, evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the related assumptions and inputs.

- Obtaining and reviewing valuation reports for investment properties held directly by the Group or through associates or joint ventures, and verifying that the fair value was determined in accordance with the valuations in the reports;
- Assessing the independence and qualifications of the valuers; and
- Evaluating the appropriateness of the valuation techniques and the reasonableness of the related assumptions and inputs.

- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements, whether due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks; and obtain audit evidence that is sufficient and appropriate to provide a basis for my opinion. The risk of not detecting a material misstatement resulting from fraud is higher than for one resulting from error, as fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omissions, misrepresentations, or the override of internal control;
- Obtain an understanding of internal control relevant to the audit in order to design audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal control;
- Evaluate the appropriateness of accounting policies used and the reasonableness of accounting estimates and related disclosures made by the Monetary Authority;
- Conclude on the appropriateness of the Monetary Authority’s use of the going concern basis of accounting and, based on the audit evidence obtained, whether a material uncertainty exists related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that a material uncertainty exists, I am required to draw attention in my auditor’s report to the related disclosures in the financial statements or, if such disclosures are inadequate, to modify my opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. However, future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure and content of the financial statements, including the disclosures, and whether the financial statements represent the underlying transactions and events in a manner that achieves fair presentation; and
- Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for the direction, supervision and performance of the Group audit. I remain solely responsible for my audit opinion.
